Please don't add functions to the public API whose only protection against UB is `assert()`. Use of `assert()` in in shared libraries as error handling for caller controlled data is a security concern (denial of service, potentially integrity problems). Further, if the library is compiled with `-DNDEBUG` we get a NULL dereference which also tends to crash the process.

The general pattern used is to declare the function as returning `int` and then take a pointer as an out-parameter:

```
int pldm_entity_node_get_remote_container_id(const pldm_entity_node *entity, uint16_t *cid)
{
    if (!entity) {
        return -EINVAL; /* Or some more appropriate error code */
    }

    *cid = entity->remote_container_id;

    return 0;
}
```

This is starting to get a bit much. Can we please break out the conditions into intermediate variables?

```
   bool match_entity_container_id;
   bool match_entity_instance_num;
   bool match_type;

   match_type = tree_node->entity.entity_type == entity.entity_type;
   match_entity_instance_num =
       tree_node->entity.entity_instance_num == entity.entity_instance_num;
   match_entity_container_id =
       tree_node->entity.entity_container_id == entity.entity_container_id;

   if (match_type && match_entity_instance_num && match_entity_container_id) {
      ...
   }
```
